description: {"blocks":[{"key":"4m442","text":"This Standard Operating Procedure is adapted from the work of the 'National Institutes of Health-Sponsored Clinical Islet Transplantation Consortium Phase 3 Trial: Manufacture of a Complex Cellular Product at Eight Processing Facilities'' following the SOP cited in the document 'Purified Human Pancreatic Islet: Qualitative and Quantitative Assessment of Islets Using Dithizone (DTZ) – Standard Operating Procedure of the NIH Clinical Islet Transplantation Consortium'","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":387},{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":469}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"9lo4l","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"8glft","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"eas6r","text":"This SOP defines the assay method used by the Human Islet Phenotyping Program (HIPP) for quantitative and qualitative determination of the Purified Human Pancreatic Islet product, post-shipment, manufactured for use in the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases (NIDDK)-sponsored research in the Integrated Islet Distribution Program (IIDP). ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"eq4u2","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"edre5","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"cb6vr","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"6rsss","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"c4nmj","text":"Dithizone (diphenyl thiocarbazone; DTZ) is an organic chemical that chelates the zinc in the insulin granules present in the beta cells of the pancreatic islets. The islet cells are stained red while the acinar cells remain unstained.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"ds95v","text":"DTZ staining is used as a lot release and as an in-process assay:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3ik1c","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"2qgst","text":"    (i) Lot release testing: DTZ staining is used to identify islets and to determine the quantity and quality of the final islet product. Islet quantity is expressed as the number of islet equivalents (IEQ), which is calculated based on the number and diameter of the islets present in the preparation, mathematically corrected for islet volume.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"kt5p","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"5cch7","text":"    (ii) In-process testing: DTZ staining is used to identify islets and to assess the effectiveness of the digestion, isolation and purification processes. The quality of the preparations is expressed as percent islet purity, and percent trapped islets. guidelines: {"blocks":[{"key":"ds16c","text":"Integrated Islet Distribution Program (IIDP) (RRID:SCR_014387): The IIDP is a funded program commissioned and funded by the NIDDK to provide quality human islets to the diabetes research community to advance scientific discoveries and translational medicine. The IIDP consists of the NIDDK, the Project Officer (PO), the External Evaluation Committee (EEC) and the CC at City of Hope (COH). The IIDP CC integrates an interactive group of academic laboratories including the subcontracted IIDP centers.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"UNDERLINE","offset":0,"length":37},{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":44},{"style":"bold","offset":45,"length":18},{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":44},{"style":"italic","offset":45,"length":18}],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":46,"length":15}],"data":[]},{"key":"b1jpm","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"smde","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"4rrtq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"dv1k5","text":"IIDP Coordinating Center (CC): Joyce Niland, Ph.D. and Carmella Evans-Molina, M.D., Ph.D. serve as Co-Principal Investigators (Co-PIs) for the IIDP Program located within the Department of Diabetes and Cancer Discovery Science at COH to coordinate the activities of the IIDP and Human Islet Phenotyping Program (HIPP). Dr. Niland, contact PI, oversees the daily activity of the IIDP staff, provides informatics/ biostatistical input, and subcontracts with the Islet Isolation Centers (IICs) to ensure the delivery of the highest quality human islets to IIDP-approved investigators.  Dr. Evans-Molina serves as the liaison to the HIPP, interacting closely to ensure that extensive, high quality phenotypic data are collected on islets distributed by the IICs.  She also facilitates the delivery of this information to both the IICs and the IIDP-approved investigators, while responding to questions, issues, or suggestions for further HIPP enhancements.”","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"UNDERLINE","offset":0,"length":29},{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":30},{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":30}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"frir7","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"b5hoq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"erq8k","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"2vjsk","text":"Human Islet Phenotyping Program (HIPP): The HIPP is a subcontracted entity of the IIDP through the COH and Vanderbilt University. The HIPP is directed by Marcela Brissova, Ph.D. and is responsible for performing specific standardized quality control assays agreed upon by both the IIDP and the HIPP, in order to provide enhanced, quality data on the human islets post-shipment, to the IIDP. The results of these assays will be approved by the CC and posted on the IIDP website for both the centers and the approved investigators to access.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":28},{"style":"italic","offset":31,"length":9},{"style":"UNDERLINE","offset":0,"length":37},{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":40}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"67vdd","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"43n48","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"4fvno","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"av1qj","text":"Percent Purity: The percentage of islets compared to all tissue present in the islet preparation (islets, acinar and ductal cells), determined by quantitative analysis of a representative sample of the islet preparation. {"blocks":[{"key":"94vql","text":"Prepare DTZ stain as described below. Observe all safety precautions when working with DMSO.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"cm6i8","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d6cq2","text":"Wearing gloves, dissolve   dithizone in   DMSO.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":25,"length":1},{"key":1,"offset":40,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"bcd7g","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"amount","mutability":"","data":{"amount":"50","guid":"2054F94004BA11EBB934C59C2831C132","id":"91882","label":"","unit":5}},"1":{"type":"amount","mutability":"","data":{"amount":"10","guid":"2F5C532004BA11EBB934C59C2831C132","id":"91883","label":"","unit":2}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"2lppv","text":"Top up to   with DPBS.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":10,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"3f1jp","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"amount","mutability":"","data":{"amount":"50","guid":"5716EB0004BA11EBB934C59C2831C132","id":"91884","label":"","unit":2}}}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"epvsr","text":"Filter the combined solution using a 0.45µm nylon filter.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"48gqb","text":"Place solution in a  conical tube and label “Dithizone Stain” with:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":20,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"as7dd","text":"♦ Preparation Date and Time","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"fobef","text":"♦ Expiration Date and Time (24 hours after preparation)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"avo6","text":"♦ Initials of person preparing solution","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"3v8cn","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"amount","mutability":"","data":{"amount":"50","guid":"A041630004BA11EBB934C59C2831C132","id":"91885","label":"","unit":2}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5jhbf","text":"Triplicate samples for islet quantitation, grading, and purity should be obtained upon receipt of the islet shipment. Triplicate samples must be taken for each count and purity assessment. Islet grading should be performed by three certified personnel, but may be performed by two personnel if three are not available. Results will be averaged for final reporting on the IIDP website. If triplicate counts of IEQ are more than 30% different, then a fourth sample should be taken and the four averaged. Date should be documented on the worksheets and Excel files for each procedure.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9hkv0","text":"Mix the final islet suspension very gently but thoroughly by inverting the islet prep in a conical 2-3 times before quickly taking a sample. (Do not swirl.) As islets settle rapidly, care must be taken to ensure a representative sample is taken. It is best to have two staff perform this procedure together, one mixing and the second taking the sample.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":141,"length":15}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7hdvn","text":"Take replicate  sample volumes from  total volume of shipment plus  CMRL medium in 35 mm dishes.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":15,"length":1},{"key":1,"offset":36,"length":1},{"key":2,"offset":67,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"115q4","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"amount","mutability":"","data":{"amount":"320","guid":"3BF109E004BB11EBB934C59C2831C132","id":"91886","label":"","unit":1}},"1":{"type":"amount","mutability":"","data":{"amount":"32","guid":"453C306004BB11EBB934C59C2831C132","id":"91887","label":"","unit":2}},"2":{"type":"amount","mutability":"","data":{"amount":"680","guid":"583536D004BB11EBB934C59C2831C132","id":"91888","label":"","unit":1}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4tih0","text":"Add  of the DTZ solution to the islet sample and allow staining for 1 – 2 minutes at room temperature. Add an additional  CMRL medium to plate before imaging.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":4,"length":1},{"key":1,"offset":121,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"c3e12","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"amount","mutability":"","data":{"amount":"50","guid":"AB026B3004BB11EBB934C59C2831C132","id":"91889","label":"","unit":1}},"1":{"type":"amount","mutability":"","data":{"amount":"1","guid":"B61C5E4004BB11EBB934C59C2831C132","id":"91890","label":"","unit":2}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"6gc6a","text":"Place a dish containing islets on stand of stereomicroscope equipped with a high-resolution camera, and swirl until all tissue is in the camera field of view at 10x magnification. Capture brightfield images at approximately 12-ms exposure and darkfield images at approximately 1.2-s exposure, each at 10x magnification. Ensure all tissue is present in image. Save all image files. Examples of islet images are shown in Figure 1.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":381,"length":47},{"style":"italic","offset":381,"length":47}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1ak29","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"2ci0c","text":"  ","type":"align-center","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"ejkv0","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"","data":{"guid":"48A8B1F004BC11EBB934C59C2831C132","height":589,"id":304696,"is_video":false,"legend":"","mime":"image/png","nestedSelector":null,"original_name":"Figure 1.png","placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jcx4bghg7.jpg","shadow":false,"source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jjt2bghg7.jpg","webp_source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jjtzbghg7.webp","width":361}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"c85kv","text":"Open the darkfield image in the cellSens software. Using the manual HSV threshold function, segment the islet tissue channel (stained red) and non-islet tissue (unstained).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"em5sh","text":"Use the custom Count and Measure algorithm to determine islet count, mean islet diameter, and area of islet and non-islet tissue in the image. Split adjacent but discrete islets using the Manually Split Objects tool to get an accurate islet count (AI). For IEQ calculation, use the Object Filter to exclude islets \u003c50µm in diameter. For Islet Purity calculation, turn off the Object Filter to include all tissue.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"1q34g","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"fb7uj","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"6006f","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"f5v7g","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"","data":{"blocks":[{"data":[],"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[{"length":115,"offset":0,"style":"italic"}],"key":"4udt","text":"Note: Islet purity analysis by cellSens began 12/6/2016; islet count and IEQ analysis by cellSens began 10/24/2017.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8rkd9","text":"Calculate the dilution factor as follows:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"krtk","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"akljl","text":"Dilution Factor = Total volume of islet preparation that sample aliquot was taken from (mL) x 1000 / Volume of sample aliquot (µL)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"3mh8k","text":"Using the islet and non-islet tissue area measurements, calculate Islet Purity using the following formula:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"937pi","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"60m2p","text":"Islet Purity (%) = Total islet tissue area / (Total islet tissue area + Total non-islet tissue area) x 100","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"4qaqd","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"5h3is","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":[]},{"key":"8gr59","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"AE5001103F6C11ED98827BA78D13E683","height":193,"id":304698,"is_video":false,"legend":"","mime":"image/jpeg","nestedSelector":null,"original_name":"Screen Shot 2022-09-28 at 3.13.50 PM.jpg","placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jjt6bghg7.jpg","shadow":false,"source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jjt4bghg7.jpg","webp_placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jjt5bghg7.webp","webp_source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jjt3bghg7.webp","width":550}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"49d6","text":"The Islet Index (II), a calculation made by dividing the IEQ by the AI, will be calculated by the system when these parameters are entered into the system. This designation determines the overall size distribution of the islets being shipped.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}
